## Project Overview
Social media management platform with multi-platform post scheduling and analytics capabilities.

## Core Components
1. Post Management
   - Schedule posts across platforms
   - Media upload and preview
   - Draft management
   - Post templates

2. Analytics
   - Platform-specific metrics
   - Custom reporting
   - Data visualization
   - Export capabilities

3. Team Features
   - Role-based access
   - Collaboration tools
   - Activity tracking
   - Workflow management

## Technical Stack
Frontend:
- Next.js
- TypeScript
- TailwindCSS
- React Components

## UI/UX Development Guidelines

### Pages to Implement
1. Authentication
   - Login (`/auth/login`)
   - Signup (`/auth/signup`)
2. Dashboard
   - Home (`/`)
   - Calendar View (`/app/calendar`)
   - Analytics Dashboard (`/app/analytics`)
3. Management
   - Team Management (`/app/team`)
   - Profile Settings (`/app/settings`)
   - Platform Integrations (`/app/integrations`)

### Core UI Requirements
- Calendar interface with month/week/day views
- Event creation modal for scheduling posts
- Sidebar with filters and calendars list
- Time-slot based event scheduling (6am-1pm format)
- User avatars for team collaboration
- Color-coded event categories
- Drag-and-drop event scheduling

### Development Workflow
1. Branch Management
   - Create feature branches from `main`
   - Use prefix `feature/ui-*` for all UI work
   - Example: `feature/ui-calendar-view`

2. Component Development
   - Create reusable components in `src/components`
   - Document props and usage
   - Include responsive designs
   - Follow existing styling patterns

3. State Management
   - Use React hooks for local state
   - Implement proper loading states
   - Handle error scenarios
   - Add proper TypeScript types

4. Testing & Preview
   - Test on multiple viewports
   - Verify accessibility
   - Check performance metrics
   - Use mock data initially

### Separation of Concerns
1. Infrastructure Team (Current Session)
   - Core authentication
   - API integration
   - Deployment configuration
   - Environment setup
   - Database management

2. UI/UX Team (Separate Session)
   - Page components
   - User interface design
   - Component library
   - Interactive features
   - Responsive layouts

### File Ownership and Development Streams

1. Infrastructure/Backend Stream
   - Core Configuration:
     - `.devinrules`: Project documentation and status
     - `deployment/*`: DigitalOcean deployment scripts
     - `nginx.conf`: Web server configuration
     - `pnpm-workspace.yaml`: Monorepo configuration
     - `tsconfig.json`: TypeScript configuration
     - `turbo.json`: Build pipeline configuration
   
   - Backend Files:
     - `packages/backend/*`: Express.js backend service
     - `packages/backend/prisma/*`: Database schema and migrations
     - `packages/backend/src/routes/*`: API endpoints
     - `packages/backend/src/services/*`: Business logic
     - `packages/backend/src/types/*`: TypeScript definitions

   - Frontend Infrastructure:
     - `packages/frontend/next.config.js`: Next.js configuration
     - `packages/frontend/src/lib/*`: Shared utilities
     - `packages/frontend/src/api/*`: API integration

2. UI/UX Stream
   - Frontend Components:
     - `packages/frontend/src/app/*`: Page components
     - `packages/frontend/src/components/*`: Reusable components
     - `packages/frontend/src/styles/*`: Styling and themes
     - `packages/frontend/src/hooks/*`: React hooks
     - `packages/frontend/public/*`: Static assets

### Coordination Rules
1. Development Process
   - UI team works in separate Devin session
   - Use mock data during development
   - Follow TypeScript interfaces
   - Regular sync via PR reviews

2. Avoid Modifying
   - Core authentication logic
   - API integration code
   - Environment configurations
   - Deployment settings

3. Preview Requirements
   - Local development server
   - Mock data for testing
   - Component isolation
   - Responsive testing

4. Documentation
   - Update component docs
   - Add usage examples
   - Document props
   - Note dependencies

Backend:
- Express.js
- PostgreSQL
- Prisma ORM
- JWT Auth

## Development Guidelines

### Environment Setup
1. Requirements
   - Node.js 18.20.7
   - pnpm 9.15.1
   - PostgreSQL 16
   - Git

2. Local Development
   ```bash
   # Install dependencies
   pnpm install

   # Setup environment
   cp .env.example .env

   # Start development servers
   pnpm dev
   ```

### Deployment Process
1. DigitalOcean Setup
   ```bash
   # Initial server setup
   ./deployment/scripts/setup.sh

   # Deploy updates
   ./deployment/scripts/deploy.sh
   ```

2. Service Management
   ```bash
   # View service status
   pm2 list

   # Check logs
   pm2 logs [frontend|backend]

   # Restart services
   pm2 restart all
   ```

3. Configuration Files
   - `nginx.conf`: Web server and reverse proxy
   - `deployment/scripts/setup.sh`: Initial server configuration
   - `deployment/scripts/deploy.sh`: Continuous deployment
   - `.env`: Environment variables

4. Health Monitoring
   - Frontend: http://omniposting.com
   - Backend: http://api.omniposting.com/health
   - Process Manager: PM2 dashboard
   - Nginx Status: systemctl status nginx

## Testing
- Unit tests: `pnpm test`
- Integration: `pnpm test:integration`
- Coverage: `pnpm test:coverage`

## Security Guidelines
1. Environment Variables
   - Never commit .env files
   - Use .env.example for templates
   - Secure credential management
   - Rotate secrets regularly

2. Authentication
   - Implement proper JWT handling
   - Use secure session management
   - Follow OAuth best practices
   - Rate limit sensitive endpoints

3. Data Protection
   - Validate all inputs
   - Sanitize database queries
   - Encrypt sensitive data
   - Regular security audits

## Contributing
1. Code Standards
   - Follow TypeScript guidelines
   - Maintain test coverage
   - Document API changes
   - Use consistent formatting

2. Pull Requests
   - Create feature branches
   - Write clear descriptions
   - Include test coverage
   - Update documentation

